<TEXT>
hispanic candidates continued to make gains in 
local state and federal elections this year and now hold 3360 
elective positions nationwide said a report released today 
the national association of latino elected and appointed 
officials said the number of hispanic elected officials increased 
by 13 percent this year based on elections from august 1987 to 
august 1988 
harry pachon national director of the association said 
measuring the number of hispanic elected officials is a good 
barometer of hispanic progress in the political arena the 
association is a nonpartisan nonprofit research organization 
with more than 3300 members 
president reagan on tuesday proclaimed this week as national 
hispanic heritage week saying people of hispanic descent have 
written countless chapters in the unique saga of the united 
states 
most of the hispanic elected officials hold municipal and school 
board seats association researcher luis baquedano said a breakdown 
of party membership was not available because many local officials 
do not run as democrats or republicans 
the association said the largest gains were made in the 
southwest with texas accounting for 1611 of the elected officials 
and new mexico coming in second with 595 texas has the nations 
secondlargest hispanic population with 41 million of the 
nations estimated 194 million hispanics 
california with the countrys largest hispanic population at 
66 million had 466 hispanic elected officials 
new york with a thirdranked hispanic population of 21 
million had 68 elected latino leaders fewer than states with 
smaller hispanic populations such as arizona with 237 elected 
officials and colorado with 157 
other states with doubledigit numbers of elected hispanics were 
florida 50 new jersey 44 illinois 28 connecticut 15 and 
washington 12 
hispanics hold 11 seats in the us house but none in the 
senate there is one hispanic governor bob martinez of florida 
</TEXT>
