<TEXT>
rep jack kemp of new york says his decision 
to join a conservative think tank in january when he leaves 
congress doesnt mean hes leaving politics completely 
the nineterm gop congressman who earlier had said he would not 
seek a 10th house term said tuesday his position as a 
distinguished fellow at the heritage foundation would be another 
phase in his career 
im not going to be in public office but i will be doing 
things before congressional committees lecturing writing 
speaking and staying active in support of those policies and issues 
and ideas that i have been associated with for a number of years 
he said 
kemp who for nearly 18 years has represented new yorks 31st 
congressional district around buffalo announced earlier this year 
that he would retire from congress at the end of this term at the 
time he was waging an unsuccessful bid for the republican 
presidential nomination 
he was mentioned as a possible running mate for george bush and 
made no secret of the fact that he would accept the job gladly 
bush instead selected sen dan quayle of indiana 
kemp said he would keep his political action committee running 
so he will have a hand in helping the candidates he supports he 
also plans to continue working for bushs presidential campaign 
and then see what happens 
i expect that bush will win and what the future holds i 
dont know he said but i think this is a good place from 
which to be active in public policy and keep my options open so 
im not ruling anything in or out 
kemp 53 in the past has been a guest lecturer at the 
foundation and has written articles for the foundations quarterly 
journal policy review the fellowship is slated to last at least 
two years he said 
kemp is a former allpro quarterback for the san diego chargers 
and the buffalo bills he first won his congressional seat in 1970 
in congress he became the architect of many economic proposals 
including the 1981 supplyside tax cuts urban enterprise zones and 
a bill passed last year that enables innercity poor people living 
in public housing to purchase their apartments 
