hampering foreign distribution of their films 
the moviemakers attorney david cole on tuesday hailed the 
decision as a rejection of a threat by usia director charles z 
wick to pull out of an international cultural exchange treaty if 
the courts rule against the agency 
wick played his bluff and the court didnt take it cole 
said in a telephone interview from the new york offices of the 
center for constitutional rights the publicinterest lawyers 
group pressing the filmmakers case 
but the usia in a statement said it remains committed to the 
ideals of the cultural exchange treaty called the beirut 
agreement which eases export of movies deemed to have educational 
scientific or cultural value 
we are very concerned about adverse court rulings which 
are interfering with our carrying out our treaty obligations 
faithfully the agency said 
the written ruling issued by us district judge a wallace 
tashima on sept 9 gives the usia 60 days to rewrite its rules for 
certifying documentary movies as educational cultural or 
scientific though the designation isnt needed to export a film 
it eases distribution by allowing dutyfree sale of movies in 70 
countries that have signed the beirut agreement or honor it 
acting on an earlier order from tashima the agency rewrote its 
rules including in the new regulations a provision allowing a film 
to be certified for dutyfree export but tagged propaganda 
tashima rejected those rules in may and ordered a second 
rewrite the latest ruling is on a request to stay that order 
pending an appeal to the 9th us circuit court of appeals 
the dispute began in 1985 when makers of seven documentary 
films on subjects ranging from nicaragua to nuclear war sued the 
usia accusing it of discriminating against movies with liberal 
themes in issuing certificates under the agreement 
agency officials have denied that politics play a role in 
certifying movies under the agreement 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

