<TEXT>
the decision by longtime un critic 
president reagan to pay 700 million in back dues to the united 
nations will save the world body from bankruptcy next month and 
keep alive its new peacekeeping force in the persian gulf 
reagans decision came two weeks before he is to address the 
159nation general assembly in his final un appearance 
while the united states has been withholding dues and 
criticizing the united nations its soviet rival has rediscovered 
the value of the organization and started paying its bills moscow 
now promotes the united nations and points a finger at the united 
states 
reagan on tuesday authorized the release of 188 million 44 
million at once and 144 million as soon as funds become available 
it appeared to be a last gesture to the world organization which 
his administration had steadily denounced as biased and bloated 
the president also directed the state department to work out a 
plan over several years for repaying 520 million in legally 
required payments to the organization 
un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar welcomed reagans 
decision and said he will feel more comfortable in making his 
final address but he added president reagan is always welcome 
perez de cuellar emphasized that financial uncertainty will 
continue until more than 70 member states pay their back dues and 
build up un reserves 
the un chief in the past has gently criticized some in the 
united states the biggest un donor for being wary of 
multilateral diplomacy and considering it an infringement on the 
us right to act unilaterally in the world arena 
foreign diplomats said recent un successes in peacemaking and 
peacekeeping in afghanistan the iraniraq war and southern africa 
appeared to be major factors in persuading the united states to 
release the legal payments it had deliberately withheld 
the united states especially welcomed un mediation of an 
accord under which more than 100000 soviet troops were to withdraw 
from afghanistan 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater announced the us 
decision tuesday saying the government recognizes the increasing 
un peacekeeping role in afghanistan namibia southwest africa 
and the gulf 
although the un reform is incomplete he said the 
progress is striking he said the united states has been 
demanding more accountability from the united nations for its 
spending 
one western diplomat speaking on condition of anonymity said 
the united states had to put its money where its mouth is 
it is difficult for the united states to continue criticizing the 
organization and withholding funds for vital operations that the 
united states welcomes 
un officials have said the united nations would be unable to 
finance the new un peacekeeping force in the gulf and pay un 
staff salaries in october without a substantial payment 
the united states is assessed more than 200 million every year 
by the united nations about a quarter of the regular budget of 
800 million 
the us government and congress had been withholding funds for 
years to pressure the united nations into political administrative 
and budgetary reforms the administration now says it is satisfied 
that reforms although imperfect are significant and are well 
under way 
that will tide the organization over its worst financial crisis 
in years but financial uncertainty will remain until other debtor 
nations pay their arrears 
un budget arrears as of july 31 were 602 million 
peacekeeping arrears totaled an additional 484 million 
the top 10 debtor nations at that time were the united states 
south africa brazil iran the soviet union argentina mexico 
israel poland and romania 
but the soviet union recently paid virtually all of its arrears 
after years of overdue accounts moscow has been seeking to promote 
the united nations as an instrument of a new kind of political 
thinking and has cited the united states for withholding dues and 
opposing multilateralism 
</TEXT>
