<TEXT>
supreme court justice harry a blackmun 
says the ideological bent of his newest colleague anthony kennedy 
is critical to the courts direction and might threaten his roe vs 
wade decision legalizing abortion 
another good indicator of what the future holds the 79yearold 
jurist suggested tuesday will be the civil rights case of 
patterson vs mclean credit union set for oral argument after the 
court begins its term oct 3 
i think the outcome of that case will be of some significance 
as to the movement of the court during the balance of the 20th 
century blackmun told law students at the university of arkansas 
at little rock 
the court stunned civil rights groups in april when it announced 
it wanted to use the patterson case to reexamine a 12yearold 
precedent that held a private allwhite school violated the law in 
refusing to consider black applicants based on their race 
the 1976 case allowed damages to be awarded against private 
parties who discriminate on the basis of race in deciding with whom 
to contract 
blackmun said an aspect of the case that has bothered him was 
the courts decision to reexamine the 1976 precedent on the 
courts own motion that is after neither of the parties brought 
up the issue 
blackmun said he sees the court as currently divided into three 
groups 
the liberals justices thurgood marshall and william j brennan 
jr 
the conservatives chief justice william h rehnquist and 
justices antonin scalia sandra day oconnor and apparently 
kennedy 
the moderates himself and justices byron r white and john 
paul stephens iii 
the division blackmun said means that all three moderates must 
align themselves with the two liberals on any given issue to take 
control of the court that the conservatives will control the court 
in some areas he said is almost a foregone conclusion since some 
of the moderates are conservative in areas he said white for 
example almost always lines up with the conservatives in criminal 
cases giving the conservatives their fivemember majority 
blackmun noted it is difficult to classify kennedy yet because 
he participated in only a few of the courts weekly conferences 
there will be a much clearer picture of the alignment next summer 
after the term concludes he said 
blackmun perhaps best known for his 1973 decision in the case 
of roe vs wade which overturned restrictive antiabortion laws in 
texas also warned that the court could reverse that decision 
during the coming term 
he indicated the ruling could turn on how faithful kennedy is to 
the judicial doctrine of stare decisis a policy of courts not 
to disturb a settled point of law 
the next question is will roe vs wade go down the drain 
blackmun said i think theres a very distinct possibility 
that it will this term you can count the votes 
commenting on blackmuns remarks douglas johnson legislative 
director of the national right to life committee accused the 
justice of interjecting himself in the presidential campaign 
apparently blackmun recognizes that roe v wade cannot survive 
merely on its constitutional merits so he is calling for cavalry 
support johnson said 
