suspected sikh militants opened fire on a 
crowd of laborers at a grain market in the northern indian state of 
punjab killing at least 20 people and wounding 60 police said 
today 
jp virdhi senior superintendent of police for the patiala 
district said 10 or 12 militants with cloth masks on their faces 
entered the main grain market in sirhind town late tuesday turned 
off the power supply and then began firing indiscriminately 
sirhind is a medieval town 119 miles southeast of amritsar 
seventeen people died on the scene and three died later in 
hospitals virdhi said in a telephone interview of those killed 
14 were hindus four were sikhs and two christians he said 
of the injured 20 were in serious condition in hospitals 
virdhi said said seven women and five children were among others 
injured 
the victims were mostly laborers from the eastern state of bihar 
who were working late into the night loading grain 
laborers come from throughout india to work in punjab because 
they can receive higher wages in the state the most fertile and 
agriculturally productive in the country 
after shooting for nearly 15 minutes into the crowd with 
chinesemade ak47 assault rifles the attackers left on 
motorcycles and motor scooters virdhi said 
sikh militants have been agitating for a separate homeland since 
1982 claiming discrimination by the majority hindu community which 
forms more than 80 percent of indias population 
the killings tuesday raised the death toll in this years bloody 
sikh campaign to 1920 most of the victims have been civilians 
more than half of them moderate sikhs who oppose the campaign for a 
sikh homeland 
sikhs form less than 2 percent of indias population of 800 
million but they are in a majority in punjab 
