iran and iraq agreed to recess their stalled peace 
talks and resume them in new york according to a un mediator 
but baghdad balked at a proposed meeting date this month 
a un mediator said he hoped to come up with a meeting date 
today 
un secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar proposed the 
temporary move to new york in the hope of unblocking the 
unmediated negotiations which opened in geneva almost three 
weeks ago 
the agreement to pick up talks shortly in new york was 
announced tuesday by un mediator jan eliasson appointed by perez 
de cuellar last week to oversee the talks in his absence 
the un chief invited the foreign ministers of the two nations 
to meet at un headquarters in new york on sept 22 but the iraqi 
delegation announced that foreign minister tariq aziz could not be 
in new york before the first week of october 
the iraqis also said they agreed to attend one meeting in new 
york only if before leaving geneva a firm date was fixed for 
returning 
the iraqis hardline stance was spelled out in a press statement 
tuesday night 
eliasson sought to play down the problem calling the question 
of dates a technical secondary issue he told journalists it 
could be solved in a smooth undramatic manner and indicated he 
hoped this could be done by today 
the main thing is the acceptance by both sides of a meeting 
in new york shortly and of the subsequent continuation of the 
talks in geneva he said 
he told a news conference earlier that both sides seem 
committed to keep the peace process going he said they also 
pledged to continue to observe the ceasefire which went into 
effect aug 20 after eight years of fighting and an estimated 1 
million dead 
the swedish diplomat acknowledged however that on issues of 
substance there has been little if any progress 
but he said the essential thing was that the peace process is 
kept alive 
the talks have bogged down over differing priorities iran wants 
the negotiations to stick to the un ceasefire resolution 
starting with withdrawal of all troops to internationally 
recognized borders 
iran holds that these borders were delineated in a 1975 treaty 
between the two countries iraq renounced the accord in 1980 
shortly before invading iran but iran says the unilateral 
repudiation violates international law 
iraq wants the talks to focus immediately on clearing the 
shattalarab waterway of silt and sunken wreckage the waterway 
provides iraq with its main outlet to the sea 
iraq also wants immediately to discuss freedom of navigation in 
the persian gulf 
iran says these are secondary issues that could be dealt with 
after the ceasefire resolution is put into full effect 
