<TEXT>
george bush has capitalized on the pledge of 
allegiance and national defense as presidential campaign issues 
scoring enough points to pull ahead of michael dukakis in two 
public opinion polls 
dukakis suffered his highest negative rating of the race in one 
of the surveys released tuesday while in the other bush was 
favored by sizable margins on the issues he has been pressing most 
strongly in the race 
bush led by eight points 47 percent to 39 percent in a cbs 
newsnew york times poll and 49 percent to 41 percent in a gallup 
poll two polls monday had it closer but two surveys last week 
also put bush ahead and found underlying movement toward him 
a los angeles times nationwide poll released today showed a dead 
heat with bush and dukakis both receiving 47 percent support among 
the most likely voters among all registered voters who were 
surveyed by the newspaper 54 percent identified bush as the 
candidate who would best ensure a strong defense 
in the gallup poll 68 percent had heard of bushs criticism of 
dukakis for vetoing a law requiring teachers to lead classes in the 
pledge and nearly half of them viewed dukakis less favorably 
because of it the rest split between rating him higher and saying 
it made no difference 
dukakis the massachusetts governor has said he acted on the 
basis of a court opinion that the law was unconstitutional but in 
the cbstimes poll 70 percent said teachers should be required to 
lead the pledge and half of them said they felt that way even if 
the requirement were unconstitutional 
bush also did well on defense twentyeight percent said he 
would make the nation stronger while only 4 percent said weaker by 
contrast 39 percent said dukakis would make us defenses weaker 
and just 13 percent said stronger the rest in both cases said 
defenses would remain unchanged 
bush even outpolled dukakis on competence an issue the 
democrat had sought to make his own fiftyone percent said bush 
would be more competent at managing the federal government while 
32 percent chose dukakis 
the cbstimes poll also found bush ranked nearly even with 
dukakis on protecting the environment an issue that traditionally 
goes to the democrats but that bush has been stressing recently 
forty percent in the gallup poll viewed dukakis unfavorably 
overall up from 32 percent last month and the highest all year for 
dukakis in the poll dukakis was rated favorably by 53 percent but 
bush won both ratings with 59 percent favorable and 35 percent 
unfavorable 
both candidates confidence ratings declined in the cbstimes 
poll fiftynine percent said they would be uneasy with dukakis in 
an international crisis up from 53 percent last month fortyseven 
percent said they would be uneasy with bush up 10 points 
