<TEXT>
nine of 10 americans reject decriminalizing all 
illicit drugs with a majority saying legalization would lead to 
increased drug use according to an abc news poll 
in addition 70 percent of those polled said they want the 
federal government to increase spending to prevent drug abuse 
the legalization of marijuana was favored by 25 percent of those 
polled but only 7 percent favored the legalization of cocaine and 
6 percent said heroin should be legal 
the nationwide telephone poll of 509 adults conducted from aug 
30 through sept 1 showed that 51 percent believed legalizing drugs 
would lead to increased drug use eleven percent said use would 
decrease and 38 percent said it would make no difference 
asked whether all illicit drugs should be legalized 9 percent 
said yes and 90 percent no 
the margin of error for the poll released tuesday was plus or 
minus 5 percentage points 
by a 2to1 margin 47 percent to 23 percent those polled said 
legalization would lead to an increase in crime not a decrease as 
some have argued twentynine percent said it would have no effect 
majorities also rejected the arguments that legalization would 
drive organized crime out of the drug business 64 percent and 
that it would make drugs less dangerous to users 55 percent 
asked which drug causes the most problems in society those 
polled said cocaine 28 percent alcohol 25 percent crack 25 
percent heroin 6 percent marijuana 4 percent and lsd 1 
percent 
twenty percent of those polled said drugs were the most 
important problem facing the country compared with 6 percent who 
listed it no 1 in an abc news poll in october 1987 
in the poll released tuesday unemployment the budget deficit 
poverty and international affairs each were listed by 7 percent as 
the most important problem facing the united states 
</TEXT>
