<TEXT>
patients at cook county hospital would have the 
right to refuse treatment by workers who carry the aids virus under 
a proposal praised by some in the medical community as an advance 
in patients rights but criticized by others as misinformed 
the recommendation was approved tuesday by the county boards 
health and hospitals committee it is expected to be endorsed by 
the full board next week becoming the first such policy for a us 
hospital officials said 
it would cover all hospital workers who routinely provide 
direct patient care including doctors and nurses 
cook county hospital director terrence hansen said the proposed 
policy is an effort to increase patients rights but others in the 
medical profession blasted the proposal wednesday 
our reaction is one of dismay said dr lonnie bristow 
speaking for the american medical association there has been no 
case in this country of a patient contracting the aids virus from a 
healthcare worker 
it is important to keep in mind that the disease is not 
transmitted by casual contact bristow a member of the amas 
board of trustees said from his berkeley calif office the 
likelihood of transmission from a healthcare worker is very 
small 
the proposed policy is not offering patients any additional 
protection it implies people should be worried he said 
this is a policy based on fear and it will do no one any 
good said dr renslow sherer who works in the aids prevention 
service at cook county hospital this is an illconceived and 
illadvised policy 
the fact that no other hospital has taken this action means 
the hospitals dont see this as a major problem said ann guild 
director of medical staff affairs for the illinois hospital 
association 
its not supported by scientific evidence that something like 
this is necessary guild said 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the bodys defenses 
against disease leaving a person prey to lifethreatening 
infections and certain cancers 
aids has struck more than 72000 people in this country since 
1979 and killed more than 40000 of them according to the national 
centers for disease control 
the virus that causes the incurable and fatal disease is 
believed to be spread through sexual intercourse shared hypodermic 
needles and from infected mothers to their infants before or during 
birth 
