<TEXT>
us industrial production rose a modest 02 
percent in august the smallest gain in five months following a 
much larger july advance the government said wednesday 
the federal reserve said the increase in august the 11th 
consecutive month without a decline followed a revised 1 percent 
july advance which had been the strongest showing since last 
october 
the august increase was in line with expectations and analysts 
said it should calm fears that the economy was overheating 
with factories operating at their highest levels in eight years 
there had been fears that rising demand pressures would spark an 
inflationary spiral but since late march the federal reserve has 
been pushing interest rates higher as a way of dampening demand and 
economists said this strategy is working 
the fears of overheating are dying down said david wyss an 
economist with data resources inc a lexington mass consulting 
firm we are not looking for a recession but we are getting 
fairly clear evidence that the economy is slowing down 
wyss predicted that the overall economy which expanded at an 
annual rate of 33 percent in the first half of the year as 
measured by the gross national product should grow at about that 
rate in the current julyseptember quarter but then begin slowing 
in the final three months of 1988 
the august increase in industrial production the smallest since 
an identical 02 percent march advance pushed output at us 
factories mines and utilities up by 53 percent over the level of 
a year ago 
manufacturing continued to grow but just did so more slowly 
coming on the heels of the big july advance said allen sinai 
chief economist of the boston co the manufacturing sector was in 
good health over the summer 
the report showed that american producers were continuing to 
benefit from record high demand for their goods overseas 
in a separate report wednesday the commerce department said 
that the countrys merchandise trade deficit narrowed dramatically 
in july to a 95 billion gap as a small increase in exports and a 
big drop in imports gave the country its smallest trade imbalance 
since december 1984 
manufacturing companies saw their output advance by 02 percent 
following a 09 percent july increase output at plants making 
durable goods items expected to last three or more years rose by 
02 percent while factories making nondurable goods had a 01 
percent increase 
autos were assembled at an annual rate of 7 million units in 
august down slightly from july but production of light trucks 
showed an increase 
production of business equipment which has been strong all 
year rose 02 percent in august and now stands 97 percent higher 
than a year ago analysts said this reflected a big investment push 
on the part of companies buying computers and other capital 
equipment 
production in the mining sector fell by 03 percent as coal 
production declined after a huge increase in july 
the nations utilities boosted production by 21 percent in 
august reflecting a continuation of the summer heat wave 
the various changes left industrial output at 1382 percent of 
its 1977 base of 100 
