utilities that contracted with the 
washington public power supply system purposely misled bond buyers 
about the need for two nuclear power plants and never intended to 
make good on their 225 billion bond debts a lawyer argued 
wednesday 
official statements made to entice investors to buy wppss bonds 
contained a number of false promises attorney tom barr said in 
the plaintiffs opening statement he represents chemical bank of 
new york which has sued on behalf of 24000 bond buyers 
we claim and we will prove that these false statements were 
made fraudulently and negligently barr said 
the defendants deny the claims of fraud saying poor judgment 
may have been used but that wppss and defendant utilities hired 
expert advisers and acted in what they believed were the best 
interests of power consumers in the northwest 
twenty people were selected last week to serve as jurors in the 
huge complex case the trial moved here from washington state 
because of pretrial publicity was expected to take months 
wppss was formed in 1957 by public utilities to build and 
operate major electric plants in washington idaho and oregon 
in the 1970s it embarked on an ambitious plan to build five 
nuclear power plants but was plagued by cost overruns and 
construction delays only one plant was completed and is operating 
in 1983 wppss defaulted on 225 billion in bonds sold for the 
fourth and fifth of those plants leaving thousands of bond buyers 
holding worthless paper and spurring a host of lawsuits the 
default was the biggest in the history of the municipal bond 
market the two nuclear plants were never completed 
barr said the 16 defendant utilities which are wppss directors 
claimed there was a need for more electricity in the northwest when 
there was not they also repeatedly changed cost estimates for the 
plants he said 
the first of 14 bond sales estimated that the two plants would 
cost 337 billion he said that was in june 1977 in may 1981 
barr said the estimate had jumped to 118 billion and the dates 
for plant completion had jumped several years 
the ultimate ace up their sleeve barr said of the 
utilities was the washington state court system 
they intended first to go to court to try to get their state 
courts to get them out of their promises he said adding that it 
worked 
the default occurred after the washington state supreme court 
ruled the 88 utilities participating in construction of the two 
plants had signed illegal contracts 
besides the 16 utilities with special ties to the supply system 
remaining defendants include two engineering firms and an adviser 
to wppss seven other utilities settled out of court with the 
plaintiffs 
