<TEXT>
israel and hungary agreed wednesday to 
gradually restore diplomatic ties that were severed 21 years ago by 
the eastern european nation israeli media reported 
the agreement came after a meeting between israeli prime 
minister yitzhak shamir and hungarian prime minister karoly grosz 
in budapest israel radio and television said 
shamir spokesman yossi ahimeir reached at his tel aviv home 
refused comment on the reports shamir arrived in budapest 
wednesday 
israel television said shamir and grosz agreed in principle to 
the gradual restoration of ties but did not set a timetable for 
upgrading diplomatic representation 
hungary along with all other soviet bloc countries except 
romania severed ties with israel after the 1967 middle east war in 
which israel captured lands of the blocs arab allies 
in the past two years the soviet union and some of its allies 
sought improved relations with israel israel and the soviet union 
have exchanged consular delegations 
israel and hungary resumed lowlevel diplomatic ties last year 
and opened interest sections the lowest form of diplomatic 
representation in budapest and tel aviv in march 
in may israeli foreign minister shimon peres made a surprise 
visit to hungary and said the hungarian government wanted to 
expand economic ties with the jewish state in 1986 trade between 
the two countries totaled about 22 million 
imre miklos hungarys state secretary for church affairs made 
a fiveday visit to israel last week and met with shamir 
after his return to hungary miklos said shamir reinforced 
israels interest in further developing relations with hungary and 
said my visit reflected an ongoing improvement in hungarianisraeli 
relations 
he added he shamir could see no reason to prevent the 
development of relations in all fields including the diplomatic 
one 
shamirs private twoday tour of hungary is the first visit by 
an israeli prime minister to a soviet bloc country other than 
romania since 1967 
on thursday shamir head of the rightwing likud bloc was 
scheduled to meet with jewish leaders and visit a synagogue in 
budapest about 80000 jews live in hungary and about 240000 jews 
of hungarian origin live in israel 
also wednesday lt gen sidney thomas weinstein us deputy 
chief of staff ended a threeday unofficial visit to hungary to 
discuss ways to improve military cooperation between the two 
countries hungarian state television reported 
weinstein reportedly the highestranking american army officer 
to visit the warsaw pact country held talks with lt gen ferenc 
szucs deputy chief of staff of the hungarian peoples army and met 
with lt gen jozsef pacsek chief of staff and deputy defense 
minister the report said 
according to hungarian television weinstein inquired about 
the hungarian defense doctrine and conferred on possibilities to 
further develop ties between the armies of the two countries 
with the political improvement between hungary and the united 
states possibilities have opened up for better military ties 
the television report said without further elaboration 
