heartstarting electrical jolts and can be operated with little 
training could save many of the 400000 americans who die each year 
of cardiac arrest according to a new report 
the machines are sophisticated versions of the defibrillators 
that doctors and paramedics have used for decades but so automated 
that they are much easier to use 
when attached to the chest the device will check the victims 
heart and deliver a shock if it finds he has suffered cardiac 
arrest a disastrous interruption in the hearts bloodpumping 
rhythm if given soon enough the shock almost always restarts the 
stalled heart 
