<TEXT>
a few years back the prospect of 14 a barrel oil 
sent shivers down many a texas spine but state economists and oil 
analysts are shrugging off the possible effects of the recent slide 
in oil prices to near twoyear lows 
optimists might attribute the change in attitude to a 
diversification of the states economy since the great oil bust of 
1986 
but analysts say the main reason for the change is that oil 
companies have grown so lean since then that prices would have to 
drop considerably further to wreak more shortterm havoc with the 
industry and the states economy 
oil futures slipped below 14 per barrel this week before 
surging back a bit after king fahd of saudi arabia called for 
better cooperation among opec members 
the october contract for delivery of west texas intermediate 
the benchmark grade of us crude rose 7 cents to settle at 1456 
a barrel on tuesday 
the october contract had skidded as low as 1375 during 
mondays trading marking the lowest level since oct 29 1986 
before rebounding on spot markets crude prices also are below 
1450 
despite the dwindling upstream profits from drilling and 
production texas refineries are profitably working around the 
clock and the integrated oil companies have streamlined enough to 
make up for the low price of crude with the relatively firm price 
of refined products 
the energy industry is just as important as it once was but 
if you look at the region and the composition of industry its a 
much smaller share said michelle michot foss senior associate 
at houstons rice center not that the others have grown so much 
but because the oil industry has gotten smaller 
the texas economy has grown less dependent on oil tax revenue 
the state had a 113 million budget surplus in the 1988 fiscal year 
despite continuing problems in the oilpatch 
in fiscal 1987 the state legislature had to raise taxes to 
cover a 57 billion deficit and meet a constitutional requirement 
for a balanced budget 
texas employment commission figures indicate the estimated 
statewide civilian workforce in oil and gas extraction declined by 
57700 jobs between december 1985 and december 1986 to 184500 
from 242200 
the houston area lost about 160000 jobs of all types during the 
first major drop in oil prices in 198283 and an additional 
130000 jobs disappeared in the 1986 price plunge officials said 
our shortterm dependency on oil during this recovery oddly 
enough is not that great but the states longterm dependency is 
significant said ray perryman director of the baylor university 
forecasting service 
texas gradual economic recovery he said has been driven 
primarily by export industries including petrochemicals paper 
aircraft and electronics 
i think that a year from today if the price of oil stays at 
that level the economic outlook in texas will be lower than 
otherwise perryman said but i dont think were going to have 
any significant problems unless the price drops below the texas 
production levels of 1150 a barrel and stays there 
tony proffitt a spokesman for state comptroller bob bullock 
also said a sustained depression in oil prices would hurt the state 
economy but the industrys importance had declined in recent 
years he noted that oil and gas revenue accounted for only 9 
percent of state economic activity compared with as much as 27 
percent at one time 
the comptrollers office reported 4905 million in oil tax 
revenue during the 1988 fiscal year and projected 5317 million in 
1989 revenue the estimated figure may have to be lowered if prices 
continue dropping proffitt said 
many analysts predict continuing softness in the market 
although there is widespread belief that current low levels are 
temporary 
however there is fear that even shortterm dips could have a 
chilling effect on the industry and score a psychological blow to 
the optimism needed in a recovering economy 
ive already seen some indications of companies making 
decisions that are a little more conservative than they would have 
been otherwise said ken miller senior consultant at the 
consulting firm purvin amp gertz inc 
this price drop is certainly nowhere near the same magnitude 
as what happened in 1986 but i think its reminding people of 
that said miller who is predicting moderate price increases in 
late 1988 some people were starting to get a little complacent 
with the price up a little bit and this is a reminder that that 
low price atmosphere is certainly still with us 
</TEXT>
