<TEXT>
the coppermining town of cananea has 
come to symbolize the birth of mexicos nationalist spirit in the 
82 years since a bloody strike pitted mexican workers against an 
american mine owner 
today a new generation of cananea miners says a government plan 
to return the nationalized but debtridden copper company to the 
private sector is like selling a historical landmark 
this is a national patrimony we feel it in our souls said 
joaquin quijano salazar general secretary of national miners union 
section 65 representing 3000 workers at cananea 25 miles south 
of the arizona border in sonora state 
under a plan to reduce government subsidies and help mexico 
overcome its severe economic crisis the administration of 
president miguel de la madrid has sold many nonessential 
stateowned companies most of them money losers 
the sale of the cananea mine would be by far the biggest 
transfer undertaken but it now appears a final decision will be up 
to carlos salinas de gortari due to take office as president in 
december 
since the failure of a 910 million bid by protexa based in 
this northern industrial city the development bank handling the 
sale said the government has received no new offers 
in a written response to a list of questions directed to its 
mexico city headquarters the national financiera bank said cananea 
now could be sold as a package deal along with another sonora 
copper mining operation mexicana del cobre 
unofficial reports say the government will ask for 2 billion 
for the two mines but quijano said that the union opposes the sale 
they can sell a company but they cant sell workers he 
said adding that some potential buyers want to purchase the mine 
without the union contract 
the cananea consolidated copper co was founded by american 
entrepeneur william c greene in 1899 
according to the labor struggle in cananea 1906 published 
by the sonora state government greene ran the mine as an american 
fiefdom 
the mexican workers at cananea were discontented because of 
the inequalities that existed between them and the foreign workers 
at the same company they also found themselves restricted 
almost without exception to the most arduous and worst paid 
jobs the book said 
on june 1 1906 2000 mexican miners rallying under the slogan 
five pesos then 10 for eight hours work went on strike 
on june 2 according to the book north americans barricaded 
in the main offices fired indiscriminately at the mexicans 
mexican police and soldiers aided by arizona rangers put down 
the rebellion june 5 and jailed its surviving leaders 
jose luis trueva a writer who is compiling a history of the 
cananea labor movement said estimates of the death toll range from 
11 to more than 100 including americans 
the mexican dead are remembered throughout mexico each labor day 
with shouts of we will not forget the martyrs of cananea 
although at least 25 labor strikes broke out between 1905 and 
1908 the cananea strike often is credited with sparking the 
mexican labor movement and with helping to launch the mexican 
revolution of 1910 
in cananea a town of 25000 people today a local junior high 
school is named the martyrs of 1906 and two monuments stand in 
memory of those who died 
the mexican government which has controlled the operations 
since the 1970s launched a multimilliondollar expansion project 
before the onset of the economic crisis in 1982 said company 
spokesman roberto rojas 
those expenditures steady devaluations in the peso and the low 
price of copper on the international market helped put cananeas 
total debt at the equivalent of 1 billion today according to 
company figures published in the august national business magazine 
expansion 
but now the improvements are complete the price of copper is 
back up over 1 a pound and cananeas sales are soaring 
in 1987 the company had net earnings of 233 million on sales 
of 1865 million a 300 percent increase from the year before 
according to expansion 
rojas estimated production this year at 125652 metric tons of 
pure copper 
quijano said the government has treated workers better than any 
of the private owners who he said carried off everything and 
left us nothing 
said quijano now that its making money they want to sell it 
we hope they dont find any buyers 
