<TEXT>
the senate today confirmed the nomination of 
investment banker nicholas f brady to serve as treasury secretary 
during the remaining four months of the reagan administration 
the 922 vote installed brady with time to spare before a 
meeting late next week in west berlin of finance ministers from the 
worlds industrial powers 
senators of both parties were anxious for a strong vote of 
confidence to strengthen bradys hand in the meeting of the g7 as 
the finance ministers group is known 
if we did not confirm nick brady he would go with a little 
bit of a cloud over his head to an important international meeting 
nothing could serve the congress or the country more than to give 
nick brady a unanimous vote of approval sen bob packwood of 
oregon ranking republican on the senate finance committee said 
shortly before the vote 
sen kent conrad dnd sounded one of the few discordant 
notes voting against the nomination after criticizing brady for 
saying during his confirmation hearing that the federal government 
could grow its way out of the budget deficit 
mr brady says dont worry well grow out of it well the 
truth is different and the truth will out conrad said 
sen harry reid dnev also voted against the nomination 
brady upon being sworn in will be the third treasury secretary 
to serve under president reagan donald regan who later became 
white house chief of staff held the cabinet post from 1981 to 
1985 turning it over to james a baker iii 
although brady is expected to do little more than serve as a 
caretaker this year he would be the most likely candidate to serve 
as treasury secretary if republican presidential candidate george 
bush wins 
the finance committee had voted 150 on tuesday to recommend 
confirmation of the popular former senator 
at the committee hearing brady promised he would reassure the 
g7 of his intent to continue the economic cooperation policies of 
his predecessor 
the steady decline of the value of the dollar since september 
1985 coordinated by the united states and its economic allies has 
been credited with reviving us sales abroad and reducing the 
trade deficit this year 
brady delivered generally upbeat remarks to the committee on the 
prospects of narrowing both the trade gap and the federal budget 
deficit 
he even managed to get credit for a stock market rally late in 
the day 
responding to senators concerns that the trade deficit still 
was too large brady urged them to give us companies time to 
respond to the fall in the value of the dollar 
we have to give the system a chance to work my prediction is 
that the trade deficit is going to come down and one of the 
surprises of the next two or three years is how fast it will come 
down he said 
analysts cited the comments as the reason for a lastminute 
surge in the price of stocks which had been slightly lower for 
much of the day traders apparently interpreted the remarks as 
hinting that the governments report on the july trade deficit 
would be favorable 
it was the government reported today that the deficit shrank to 
95 billion the lowest in nearly four years 
brady also said growing overseas investment in the united 
states which has risen as foreigners purchase us assets with the 
dollars they earn from selling goods here can be taken as a sign 
of the economys strength and of foreigners faith in it 
on the federal budget deficit brady praised both the 
administration and congress for their efforts which have whittled 
the deficit from 220 billion in 1986 to an estimated 150 billion 
this year 
i do think we can grow our way out of this he said adding 
at another point i see no reason at this moment why taxes have 
to be raised 
sen max baucus dmont urged brady to offer more than 
platitudes on the budget brady declined to recommend 
specifics but promised to present congress with new ideas for 
reducing the deficit by the end of the year 
sen lloyd bentsen dtexas the chairman of the finance 
committee and the democratic vice presidential candidate gave 
brady a warm endorsement even though brady is a close adviser to 
bush 
nick brady is a friend and former colleague and in my opinion 
is a man who is well qualified to be treasury secretary bentsen 
said its a big job a tough job but youre used to tough 
jobs 
in his latest government assignment brady headed a presidential 
task force that studied the causes of the october stock market 
crash his report called for greater regulation over some aspects 
of the markets and was met with a cold shoulder by the 
administration 
brady said market reforms put in place since the crash have been 
on the right track declining to criticize the administration 
for not doing everything his commission advised 
im not sure we were 100 percent right we did our work in 60 
days he said 
on another matter brady said federal savings and loan 
regulators have as much as they can spend for now on sampl rescues 
and he said he saw no reason for now for a taxpayer bailout of 
the industry 
bradys greatgrandfather founded electric utilities that later 
became part of consolidated edison co and his grandfather started 
a precursor of dodge motor co now a division of chrysler corp 
the family also founded purolator co 
brady 58 is cochairman of dillon read amp co an oldline wall 
