<TEXT>
a federal judge today approved the partial 
merger of detroits two daily newspapers under a joint operating 
arrangement granted earlier by thenattorney general edwin meese 
iii 
us district judge george revercombs decision approving the 
partial merger of the detroit free press and the detroit news came 
a month after the deal was temporarily put on hold by court order 
to give opponents a chance to mount a legal challenge 
revercomb said the stay issued last month blocking the merger 
will be allowed to expire at 715 pm edt saturday 
the court finds that the attorney general was not unreasonable 
in finding that the free press a newspaper that has incurred and 
will continue to incur losses that would already have led to its 
demise were it not owned by a large corporate parent is a failing 
newspaper he said 
william b schultz who represented the plaintiffs would not 
comment on the decision and would not say whether he planned an 
appeal until he has had an opportunity to read the opinion and 
consult with his clients 
michigan citizens for an independent press a group of readers 
and advertisers in the detroit area had contended that the free 
press owned by knightridder inc was not a failing newspaper 
entitled to antitrust exemptions under the 1980 newspaper 
preservation act 
the group noted that meese approved the joint operating 
arrangement before he left office even though an administrative law 
judge and the justice departments antitrust division had 
recommended against it 
opponents of the partial merger represented by ralph naders 
public citizen litigation group argued that the free press and the 
news had each cut advertising and circulation rates to drive the 
other out of business 
the publishers willingness to suffer losses for several years 
was sustained by the knowledge that the two dailies might 
eventually qualify for a joint operating agreement merging the two 
publications commercial operations the opponents contended 
but revercomb concluded that meese was not unreasonable in 
concluding that the free press was primarily motivated by 
competitive aims not a joa in its recent business strategies 
the judge dismissed the plaintiffs argument that meeses 
findings were flawed because he accepted the factual findings but 
not the conclusions of the administrative law judge it is not 
clear that the attorney general disagreed with the law judges 
fact findings as much much as his inferences derived from facts 
the administrative law judges finding shows that the prospect 
of a joa played at most a secondary or supporting role in the 
newspapers motivations revercomb said 
the justice department maintained in court last week there was 
no evidence of collusion between the free press and the news 
purchased by the gannett co inc in 1986 several months before 
the two papers sought the joint operating agreement 
knightridder inc has threatened to close the morning free 
press which has lost 100 million over the last nine years unless 
the partial merger was allowed to go forward 
at a hearing last week knightridders attorney clark 
clifford said the detroit area would lose 2200 jobs if the free 
press closed compared to the 600 to 800 layoffs that would result 
from the consolidation of the two newspapers business advertising 
and circulation departments 
under the proposed joint operating agreement the papers would 
maintain separate editorial staffs to put out separate daily 
editions combined editions would be published on weekends 
clifford said the free press was powerless to cut losses by 
raising its prices unless the news first raised its circulation and 
advertising rates 
the news which has also sustained significant losses was 
determined to drive the free press out of business if a joint 
operating agreement was not approved he said 
according to the audit bureau of circulation the free press had 
a daily circulation last year of 638720 daily compared to the 
news 678720 on sundays the news held a slightly larger lead 
839319 to 724342 
