aluminum co of america said wednesday that 
7000 salaried employees in its domestic aluminum operations will 
participate in a profitsharing plan beginning this year 
officials said the plan would create a profitsharing pool when 
the companys us operations exceed a return of 6 percent on 
assets they said employees would share 17 percent of profits above 
this threshold 
alcoa officials said individual payouts will vary with profits 
and the number of employees involved the plan is retroactive to 
jan 1 the company said 
alcoa said the payout could amount to about 7 percent of each 
employees base salary if secondhalf 1988 profits equal firsthalf 
profits 
in contract negotiations three weeks ago the company offered a 
profitsharing plan to union employees that would amount to up to 
1300 for bluecollar workers based on alcoas expected 1988 
profits 
the united steelworkers of america union said it rejected the 
plan as inadequate and said it opposed the companys plan to extend 
it to salaried whitecollar workers 
on aug 24 the usw and the aluminum brick and glass workers 
unions broke off early negotiations with alcoa after rejecting 
offers that included profitsharing an immediate ratification 
bonus annual lump sum bonuses an improved medical insurance 
option and increased pension benefits 
usw negotiator george becker said the talks ended because alcoa 
would not address several key issues including wage and 
pension increases 
the unions sought new contracts to recover concessions 
negotiated in 1986 when the aluminum industry faced difficult 
economic times 
