the regions 410 billion debt which does not mean decreeing a 
moratorium or creating a debtors club 
he said it could mean reaching agreement on a common negotiating 
framework which would include linking debt payments to export 
income limiting interest rates and paying according to the market 
value of the debts 
sela must take a serious initiative regarding the foreign 
debt perez del castillo told delegates at the opening of the 
technical meeting of selas 14th annual council the threeday 
ministerial level meeting begins sept 19 
we are convinced that the solutions to the regions problems 
will not come from abroad latin america must make a united effort 
to generate its own initiatives he said 
he also recommended that latin america use its annual 65 
billion in imports from industrialized nations as a negotiating 
tool to equalize trade in the face of growing protectionism 
everything the region exports is negotiated but what we 
import is not negotiated this form of commercial relations must 
change he said 
perezs call for greater regional action comes as the 
international monetary fund and the world bank which begin their 
annual assembly sept 27 in west berlin admit that their 
marketoriented approach to solving the latin american debt problem 
has not had the desired results 
the imf lends to debtors which agree to adopt austerity policies 
to promote economic stability but latin american debtors claim 
that the policies limit their ability to grow out of their debts 
in its 1987 annual report the imf notes that the debt burden 
was a key factor in causing latin american economies to shrink by 
15 percent overall last year 
